ng vs exact match). Mocking file I/O would hide these. Integration testing with real files catches them.","test_description":"Create a real package.json (or requirements.txt) with 5 dependencies including 'lodash@^4.17.0'. Run the modify function to bump lodash to '^5.0.0'. Verify the output file is valid JSON/YAML, lodash version is updated, and all other 4 dependencies are exactly unchanged (including indentation, order, and any inline comments).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The auto-generated pull request is created on the real repository with the correct single-dependency diff","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Creating a PR requires real git operations (clone/branch/commit/push) and GitHub API calls. Real failure modes: (1) git branch creation fails due to naming or permissions, (2) the diff includes unexpected files, (3) GitHub API returns an error or creates PR with wrong metadata, (4) commit history is malformed. Neither mocking git nor mocking GitHub alone would catch all these—you need real subprocess/network behavior.","test_description":"Use a real test repository (local git + mocked GitHub API, or a test repo on GitHub). Run the PR creation for a manifest bump. Verify: (a) a new branch is created and pushed, (b) the PR is created with exactly one commit containing one file change (the manifest), (c) the diff shows only the version line changed for one dependency, (d) PR title/description include the dependency name and new version.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.95,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A major version bump is correctly identified as a breaking change based on semver comparison","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Semver comparison (e.g., '1.0.0' → '2.0.0') is pure, deterministic logic. No I/O, no external calls, no state. Unit tests 